# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: photography
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:photography/135-film] The term 135 was introduced by Kodak in 1934 as a designation for 35 mm film specifically for still photography, perforated with Kodak Standard perforations.
[src:photography/135-film] It quickly grew in popularity, surpassing 120 film by the late 1960s to become the most popular photographic film size.
[src:photography/135-film] Despite competition from formats such as 120, 828, 126, 110, and APS, it remains the most popular film size today.
[src:photography/135-film] The size of the 135 film frame with its frame's aspect ratio of 2:3 has been adopted by many high-end digital single-lens reflex and digital mirrorless cameras, commonly referred to as "full frame".
[src:photography/135-film] Even though the format is much smaller than historical medium format and large format film, being historically referred to as *miniature format* or *small format*, it is much larger than image sensors in most compact cameras and smartphone cameras.
[src:photography/135-film] The engineering standard for this film is controlled by ISO 1007 titled '135-size film and magazine'.
[src:photography/135-film] The 135 film size is derived from earlier still cameras using lengths of 35 mm movie film, which had the same size but with different perforations.
[src:photography/135-film] The 35 mm film standard for motion picture film was established in Thomas Edison's lab by William Kennedy Laurie Dickson.
[src:photography/135-film] Dickson took 70 mm film stock supplied by George Eastman's Eastman Kodak Company.
[src:photography/135-film] The 70 mm film was cut lengthwise into two equal width (35 mm) strips, spliced together end to end, and then perforated along both edges.
[src:photography/135-film] The original picture size was 18×24 mm (half the full frame size later used in still photography).
[src:photography/135-film] There were four perforations on each side of a motion picture frame.
[src:photography/135-film] While the Leica camera popularized the format, several 35 mm still cameras used perforated movie film before the Leica was introduced in the 1920s.
[src:photography/135-film] The first patent for one was issued to Leo, Audobard, and Baradat in England in 1908.
[src:photography/135-film] The first full-scale production camera was the Homéos, a stereo camera produced by Jules Richard in 1913 and sold until 1920.
[src:photography/135-film] It took 18x24 mm stereo pairs and used two Tessar lenses.
[src:photography/135-film] In 1909, the French Étienne Mollier designed a device for small-format photography, the "Cent-Vues", which used the 35 mm perforated film to take consecutive hundred views in 18×24 mm.
[src:photography/135-film] He manufactured it, won the gold medal in the Concours Lépine, and in 1910 sold at a small scale and without much success.
[src:photography/135-film] The first big-selling 35 mm still camera was the American Tourist Multiple, which also appeared in 1913, at a cost of $175 (~5,600 US Dollars in 2024) The first camera to take full-frame 24×36 mm exposures seems to be the Simplex, introduced in the U.S. in 1914.
[src:photography/135-film] It took either 800 half-frame or 400 full-frame shots on 50 ft (15.2 m) rolls.
[src:photography/135-film] The Minigraph, by Levy-Roth of Berlin, another half-frame small camera was sold in Germany in 1915.
[src:photography/135-film] The patent for the Debrie Sept camera, a combination 35 mm still and movie camera was issued in 1918; the camera sold from 1922.
[src:photography/135-film] The Furet camera made and sold in France in 1923 took full-frame 24x36 mm negatives, and was the first cheap small 35 mm camera of similar appearance to more modern models.
[src:photography/135-film] The Leica Camera designed by Oskar Barnack used 35 mm film, and proved that a format as small as 24 mm × 36 mm was suitable for professional photography.
[src:photography/135-film] Although Barnack designed his prototype camera around 1913, the first experimental production run of ur-Leicas (Serial No.
[src:photography/135-film] Full-scale production of the Leica did not begin until 1925.
[src:photography/135-film] While by that time, there were at least a dozen other 35 mm cameras available, the Leica was a success.
[src:photography/135-film] It came to be associated with the format, mostly because of this 35 mm popularity, as well as the entire company legacy.
[src:photography/135-film] Early Leica cameras are considered highly collectable items.
[src:photography/135-film] The original Leica prototype holds the record as being the world's most expensive camera, selling for €2.16 million in 2012.
[src:photography/135-film] In the earliest days, the photographer had to load the film into reusable cassettes and, at least for some cameras, cut the film leader.
[src:photography/135-film] In 1934, Kodak introduced a *135* daylight-loading single-use cassette.
[src:photography/135-film] This cassette was engineered so that it could be used in both Leica and Zeiss Ikon Contax cameras along with the camera for which it was invented, namely the Kodak Retina camera.
[src:photography/135-film] The Retina camera and this daylight loading cassette were the invention of Dr.
[src:photography/135-film] August Nagel's company in December, 1931, and began marketing the *Kodak Retina* in the summer of 1934.
[src:photography/135-film] The first Kodak Retina camera was a Typ 117.
[src:photography/135-film] The 35 mm Kodak Retina camera line remained in production until 1969.
[src:photography/135-film] Kodak also introduced a line of American made cameras that were simpler and more economical than the Retina.
[src:photography/135-film] Argus, too, made a long-lived range of 35 mm cameras; notably the Argus C3.
[src:photography/135-film] Kodak launched 135-format Kodachrome colour film in 1936.
[src:photography/135-film] AGFA followed with the introduction of *Agfacolor Neu* later in the same year.
[src:photography/135-film] The designations *235* and *435* refer to 35 mm film in daylight-loading spools, that could be loaded into Contax or Leica style reusable cassettes, respectively, without need of a darkroom.
[src:photography/135-film] The *335* was a daylight loading spool for the 24 × 23 mm stereo format.
[src:photography/135-film] Reflex viewfinders, both twin-and single-lens, had been used with earlier cameras using plates and rollfilm.
[src:photography/135-film] The first 35 mm single-lens reflex (SLR) was the Kine Exakta, introduced in 1936.
[src:photography/135-film] World War II interrupted development of the type.
[src:photography/135-film] After the war, Exakta resumed development and the Contax S model with the now familiar pentaprism viewing feature was introduced in 1949.
[src:photography/135-film] In the 1950s, the SLR also began to be produced in Japan by such companies as Asahi and Miranda.
[src:photography/135-film] Asahi's Pentax introduced the instant-return mirror, important for the popularity of SLRs; until then, the viewfinder on an SLR camera blanked as the mirror sprang out of the optical path just before taking the picture, returning when the film was wound on.
[src:photography/135-film] Nikon's F model, introduced in March 1959, was a system camera that greatly improved the quality and utility of 35 mm format cameras, encouraging professionals (especially photojournalists) to switch from larger format cameras to the versatile, rugged, and fast SLR design.
[src:photography/135-film] Numerous other film formats waxed and waned in popularity, but by the 1970s, interchangeable-lens SLR cameras and smaller rangefinders, from expensive Leicas to "point-and-shoot" pocket cameras, were all using 35 mm film, and manufacturers had proliferated.
[src:photography/135-film] Colour films improved, both for print negatives and reversal slides, while black-and-white films offered smoother grain and faster speeds than previously available.
[src:photography/135-film] Since 35 mm was preferred by both amateur and professional photographers, makers of film stock have long offered the widest range of different film speeds and types in the format.
[src:photography/135-film] The DX film-speed encoding system was introduced in the 1980s, as were single-use cameras pre-loaded with 35 mm film and using plastic lenses of reasonable enough quality to produce acceptable snapshots.
[src:photography/135-film] Automated all-in-one processing and printing machines made 35 mm developing easier and less expensive, so that quality colour prints became available not only from photographic specialty stores, but also from supermarkets, drugstores, and big box retailers, often in less than an hour.
[src:photography/135-film] In 1996, a smaller format called Advanced Photo System (APS) was introduced by a consortium of photographic companies in an attempt to supersede 135 film.
[src:photography/135-film] Due in part to its small negative size, APS was not taken seriously as a professional format, despite the production of APS SLRs.
[src:photography/135-film] In the point-and-shoot markets at which the format was primarily aimed, it enjoyed moderate initial success, but still never rivalled the market penetration of 135.
[src:photography/135-film] Within five years of its launch, cheap digital compact cameras started becoming widely available, and APS sales plummeted.
[src:photography/135-film] Introductory 35 mm SLRs, compact film point-and-shoot cameras, and single-use cameras continue to be built and sold by a number of makers.
[src:photography/135-film] Leica introduced the digital Leica M8 rangefinder in 2007, but continues to make its M series rangefinder film cameras and lenses.
[src:photography/135-film] A digital camera back for the Leica R9 SLR camera was discontinued in 2007.
[src:photography/135-film] On March 25, 2009, Leica discontinued the R9 SLR and R-series lenses.
[src:photography/135-film] By the early 2020s, film photography, particularly 35 mm photography, was experiencing a resurgence in popularity.
[src:photography/135-film] In a 2021 PetaPixel survey, 75% of respondents expressed interest in newly manufactured analog cameras.
[src:photography/135-film] Kodak reported in 2022 that it was having trouble keeping up with demand for 35 mm film.
[src:photography/135-film] In 2024, the Pentax 17 and the Aflie TYCH+ 35 mm cameras were released, both using the half-frame format to conserve film.
[src:photography/135-film] Retrospekt and Mattel put out the Malibu Barbie FC-11 35 mm camera.
[src:photography/135-film] In September 2024, MiNT Camera took pre-orders for the Rollei 35AF, an update of the Rollei 35.
[src:photography/135-film] Kodak offered six 35 mm film cameras for sale as of October 2024, including the Ektar H35N, another half-frame camera.
[src:photography/135-film] Individual rolls of 135 film are enclosed in single-spool, light-tight, metal cassettes, also known as film canisters, to allow cameras to be loaded in daylight.
[src:photography/135-film] The film is clipped or taped to a spool and exits via a slot lined with flocking.
[src:photography/135-film] The end of the film is cut on one side to form a leader.
[src:photography/135-film] It has the same dimensions and perforation pitch as 35 mm movie print film (also called "long pitch", KS-1870, whereas 35 mm professional motion picture camera films are always "short pitch", BH-1866).
[src:photography/135-film] Most cameras require the film to be rewound before the camera is opened.
[src:photography/135-film] Some motorized cameras unwind the film fully upon loading and then expose the images in reverse order, returning the film to the cassette; this protects all exposed frames (except the last one or two), should the camera back be accidentally opened; unexposed film gets spoiled, however.
[src:photography/135-film] Disposable cameras use the same technique so that the user does not have to rewind.
[src:photography/135-film] Since 1983, most film cassettes have been marked with a DX encoding six-digit barcode pattern, which uses a DX number to identify the manufacturer and film type (and thus processing method), and the number of exposures, for the use of photofinishing laboratories.
[src:photography/135-film] Conforming cameras detect at least some of these areas; only three contacts are needed to set a light meter for the four most popular film speeds.
[src:photography/135-film] The 135 film has been made in several emulsion types and sensitivities (film speeds) described by ISO standards.
[src:photography/135-film] Since the introduction of digital cameras the most usual films have colour emulsions of ISO 100/21° to ISO 800/30°.
[src:photography/135-film] Films of lower sensitivity (and better picture quality) and higher sensitivity (for low light) are for more specialist purposes.
[src:photography/135-film] There are colour and monochrome films, negative and positive.
[src:photography/135-film] Monochrome film is usually panchromatic; orthochromatic has fallen out of use.
[src:photography/135-film] Film designed to be sensitive to infrared radiation can be obtained, both monochrome and with false-colour (or pseudocolour) rendition.
[src:photography/135-film] More exotic emulsions have been available in 135 than other roll-film sizes.
[src:photography/135-film] The term *135 format* usually refers to a 24×36 mm film format, commonly known as 35 mm format.
[src:photography/135-film] The 24×36 mm format is common to higher-end digital image sensors, where it is typically referred to as *full-frame* format.
[src:photography/135-film] On 135 film, the typical cameras produce a frame where the longer dimension of the 24×36 mm frame runs parallel to the length of the film.
[src:photography/135-film] The perforation size and pitch are according to the standard specification KS-1870.
[src:photography/135-film] For each frame, the film advances 8 perforations.
[src:photography/135-film] This allows for 2 mm gaps between frames.
[src:photography/135-film] Camera models typically have different locations for the sprocket which advances the film.
[src:photography/135-film] Therefore, each camera model's frame may vary in position relative to the perforations.
[src:photography/135-film] The film is approximately 0.14 mm thick.
[src:photography/135-film] Other image formats have been applied to 135 film, such as the half-frame format of 18×24 mm which earned some popularity in the 1960s, and the 24×24 mm of the Robot cameras.
[src:photography/135-film] The successful range of Olympus Pen F cameras utilized the smaller half-frame size, allowing the design of a very compact SLR camera.
[src:photography/135-film] Unusual formats include the 24×32 mm and 24×34 mm on the early Nikon rangefinders, and 24×23 mm for use with some stereo cameras.
[src:photography/135-film] In 1967, the Soviet KMZ factory introduced a 24×58 mm panoramic format with its Horizont camera (descendants of which are called, in the Roman alphabet, Horizon).
[src:photography/135-film] In 1998, Hasselblad and Fuji introduced a 24×65 mm panoramic format with their XPan/TX-1 camera.
[src:photography/135-film] There is also a 21×14 mm format used by Tessina subminiature camera.
[src:photography/135-film] The film is available in lengths for varying numbers of exposures.
[src:photography/135-film] The standard full-length roll has always been 36 exposures (assuming a standard 24×36 frame size).
[src:photography/135-film] Through about 1980, 20 exposure rolls were the only shorter length with widespread availability.
[src:photography/135-film] Since then, 20 exposure rolls have been largely discontinued in favour of 24- and 12-exposure rolls.
[src:photography/135-film] A camera that uses less than the maximum distance between the spools may be able to make one additional exposure.
[src:photography/135-film] Self-loading cameras that load the film after being closed don't spoil the additional length provided for conventional loading and can make that additional length available for two or three additional exposures.
[src:photography/135-film] The same length can be available for exposure in any camera if it is loaded without exposing the film to light, e.g. in a dark room or a dark bag.
[src:photography/135-film] A 27-exposure disposable camera uses a standard 24-exposure cassette loaded in the dark.
[src:photography/135-film] Other, mostly shorter, lengths have been manufactured.
[src:photography/135-film] There have been some 6-, 8-, 10-, and 15-exposure rolls given away as samples, sometimes in disposable cameras, or used by insurance adjusters to document damage claims.
[src:photography/135-film] Twelve-exposure rolls have been used widely in the daily press.
[src:photography/135-film] Photographers who load their own cassettes can use any length of film – with a thinner film base, up to 45 exposures will fit.
[src:photography/135-film] The Ilford HP black-and-white film, on a thin polyester base, allowed 72 exposures in a single cassette.
[src:photography/135-film] They produced special reels and tanks to allow this to be processed.
[src:photography/135-film] Digital sensors are available in various sizes.
[src:photography/135-film] Professional DSLR cameras usually use digital image sensors which approximate the dimensions of the 35 mm format, sometimes differing by fractions of a millimetre on one or both dimensions.
[src:photography/135-film] Since 2007, Nikon has referred to their 35 mm format by the trade mark FX.
[src:photography/135-film] Other makers of 35 mm format digital cameras, including Leica, Sony, and Canon, refer to their 35 mm sensors simply as full frame.
[src:photography/135-film] Most consumer DSLR cameras use smaller sensors, with the most popular size being APS-C which measures around 23×15 mm (giving it a crop factor of 1.5–1.6).
[src:photography/135-film] Compact cameras have smaller sensors with a crop factor of around 3 to 6.
[src:photography/135-film] Most smartphones (as of 2024) have a default aspect ratio of 4:3 (1.33).
[src:photography/135-film] Mimicking 35mm film in a smartphone requires cropping to a 3:2 (1.5) aspect ratio.
[src:photography/135-film] For an authentic homage, one can apply creative digital filters like the ones commonly used in Instagram that map the colour profile to a characteristic look.
[src:photography/135-film] Different brands of 35mm film would achieve the creative colour profile through a chemical process.
[src:photography/135-film] For example Fuji Velvia film gave the photo a characteristic of saturated colours under daylight, high contrast, and exceptional sharpness.
[src:photography/135-film] A true normal lens for 35 mm format would have a focal length of 43 mm, the diagonal measurement of the format.
[src:photography/135-film] However, lenses of 43 mm to 60 mm are commonly considered *normal* lenses for the format, in mass production and popular use.
[src:photography/135-film] Common focal lengths of lenses made for the format include 24, 28, 35, 50, 85, 105, and 135 mm.
[src:photography/135-film] Most commonly, a 50 mm lens is the one considered *normal*; any lens shorter than this is considered a *wide angle* lens and anything above is considered a *telephoto* lens.
[src:photography/135-film] Even then, wide angles shorter than 24 mm is called an *extreme wide angle*.
[src:photography/135-film] Lenses above 50 mm but up to about 100 mm are called short telephoto or sometimes, as *portrait telephotos*, from 100 mm to about 200 mm are called *medium* telephotos, and above 300 mm are called *long* telephotos.
[src:photography/135-film] With many smaller formats now common (such as APS-C), lenses are often advertised or marked with their "35 mm equivalent" or "full-frame equivalent" focal length as a mnemonic, due to the historic prevalence of the 35 mm format.
[src:photography/135-film] This 'equivalent' is computed by multiplying (a) the true focal length of the lens by (b) the ratio of the diagonal measurement of the native format to that of the 35 mm format.
[src:photography/135-film] As a result, a lens for an APS-C (18×24 mm) format camera body with a focal length of 40 mm, might be described as "60 mm (35 mm equivalent)".
[src:photography/135-film] Although its true focal length remains 40 mm, its angle of view is equivalent to that of a 60 mm lens on a 35 mm format (24×36 mm) camera.
[src:photography/135-film] Another example is the lens of the 2/3 inch format Fujifilm X10, which is marked with its true zoom range "7.1–28.4 mm" but has a 35 mm-equivalent zoom range of "28–112 mm".
[src:photography/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] In photography, the **35 mm equivalent focal length** is a measure of the angle of view for a particular combination of a camera lens and film or image sensor size.
[src:photography/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] The term is popular because in the early years of digital photography, most photographers experienced with interchangeable lenses were most familiar with the 35 mm film format.
[src:photography/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] On any 35 mm film camera, a 28 mm lens is a wide-angle lens, and a 200 mm lens is a long-focus lens.
[src:photography/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] The 35 mm equivalent focal length of a particular lens–sensor combination is the focal length that one would need for a 35 mm film camera to obtain the same angle of view.
[src:photography/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] Two lens-sensor combinations with the same 35 mm equivalent focal length are expected to have the same angle of view.
[src:photography/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] Most commonly, the 35 mm equivalent focal length is based on equal *diagonal* angle of view.
[src:photography/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] This definition is also in the CIPA guideline DCG-001.
[src:photography/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] Alternatively, it may sometimes be based on *horizontal* angle of view.
[src:photography/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] 35 mm equivalent focal lengths are calculated by multiplying the actual focal length of the lens by the crop factor of the sensor.
[src:photography/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] Quoted 35 mm equivalent focal lengths typically ignore depth of field (DOF), which depends on both focal length and aperture.
[src:photography/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] The DOF of smaller sensors is deeper at a given f number, due to the smaller absolute aperture diameters corresponding to shorter focal length lenses.
[src:photography/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] Equivalent depth of field can be calculated the same way using the crop factor.
[src:photography/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] For example, a 50mm f/2 lens on a 2× crop factor Micro Four Thirds camera would be equivalent to a 100 mm (= 2×50 mm) f/4 (= f/(2×2)) lens on a full-frame digital SLR in terms of field of view, depth of field, total light gathered, and diffraction effects.
[src:photography/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] However for the purposes of exposure calculations the aperture does not change for different sensor sizes.
[src:photography/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] A standard 35 mm film image is 36 mm wide by 24 mm tall (35 mm refers to the height of the film including the perforations for film transport), and the diagonal is 43.3 mm.
[src:photography/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] For historical reasons, sensor size specifications such as 1/2.5" do not match the actual sensor size, but are a bit larger (typically about a factor of 1.5) than the actual sensor diagonal.
[src:photography/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] This is because these sensor size specifications refer to the size of a camera tube, while the usable sensor size is about 2/3 of the size of the tube.
[src:photography/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] Tubes are not used on digital cameras, but the same specifications are used.
[src:photography/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] Apart from the width- and diagonal-based 35 mm equivalent focal length definitions, there is a third definition: *EFL* = 50 *f* /*d* mm.
[src:photography/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] However, it is not clear to what extent this definition is used.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] 360 photography is used primarily by ecommerce websites, to give shoppers a more realistic impression of a product than static images.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] The use of interactive 360 spins has been linked to an increase in sales conversions and lower returns of unwanted goods.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] There are 3 types of 360 photography spin: single-row spins, multi-row spins and twin-axis spins.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] Single-row spins are the most commonly used type of 360 spin because they are the easiest to create.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] One row of photos is usually sufficient to give a lifelike impression of an object.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] These spins can be moved left and right only.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] They are often composed of 36 images (each separated by 10 degrees), though any number of images can be used.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] More frames per rotation will provide a more fluid rotation; fewer frames will feel more jumpy.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] While the cost of 360 photography falls and bandwidth increases, spins with 72 or more frames are becoming more commonplace, for their smoother, sophisticated experience.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] Multi-row spins (also known as 3D spins) can be rotated up and down as well as left and right.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] These can be in the form of 'hemi-spherical' or 'full-spherical' product views.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] They are composed of 360 product image sets shot at multiple rows.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] Each row is photographed at a different camera angle, allowing the product to be viewed from multiple perspectives.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] Multi-row spins require more time and effort to photograph, so they are suited to products that benefit from being viewed from above and/or underneath.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] Photographers typically capture 360 photography in a photography studio by using a turntable, camera, tripod, lights and a white background.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] To obtain a pure white background, a white lightbox or light tent can be used to help light the object evenly, though these can flatten the image, so some photographers use a white sheet or white card in the background.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] Bottom lit turntables or a clear-acrylic stand placed on top of a turntable can help eliminate shadows.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] Turntables used by 360 product photographers are usually powered, for automatic, precision rotation.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] A product is placed in the center of the turntable and a camera, typically mounted on a tripod, captures photos of the product at even internals (ex.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] 72 frames = 1 capture every 5 degrees) as the turntable rotates.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] This process typically involves capturing multiple images from evenly spaced angles using controlled lighting conditions, followed by assembling the frames into an interactive sequence that allows users to rotate the product seamlessly.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] Specialized 360 photography turntables work in stop motion - pausing the rotation when each photo is captured to ensure for a sharp image.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] Basic turntables rotate continuously, which can cause slightly blurred photos if shooting at a slower shutter speed.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] These motorized continuous spin turntables but are suitable for capturing video, which can later be converted to a 360 spin.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] Some photography turntables can be connected by USB cable to computer and/or camera, allowing remote shutter release or USB to capture the images.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] Such automation speeds up the photography process, which is an important consideration when hundreds or thousands of products are to be photographed.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] Further automation can be achieved by employing robotic arms to move the camera up and over an object, to quickly capture multi-row spins.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] Robotic equipment is typically employed by specialist 360 photography studios, enabling them to capture high quality photos rapidly.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] Such equipment has helped reduce the cost of 360 photography to approximately 20-40 USD per product for simple products such as shoes, when photographed in large batches.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] Prices are higher for reflective objects, large objects and garments worn on a model or mannequin.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] All-in-one lightbox machines are a simpler method for capturing spins.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] These machines have an automated rotating turntable with lighting all around and above.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] They connect to a camera and computer, for automated capture.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] Amateur photographers can capture 360 spins on a low budget by using a simple lazy susan instead of a powered turntable.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] The photographer can manually rotate the turntable between each frame.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] This is a slow process, thus impractical for large volume of making it an uncommon method of capturing 360 spins.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] Thus, specialized 360 product photography tools are suggested for high volume work.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] The final method of creating 360 degree spins is by using 3D CAD modelling software.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] A product model can be constructed by a skilled 3D model designer, then rendered as a series of static JPEG/PNG images ready for use.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] Once all the images for a complete rotation have been captured, they normally require refinement in a photo-editing program with batch editing capability.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] The typical edits required are to crop closer to the object edge, mask out any background objects, adjust the colour balance to match the products true colour and adjust colour levels to whiten the background.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] Most ecommerce sites wish to display 360 spins against a pure white background, which is not usually achieved direct from the camera.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] Batch editing can be applied in dedicated 360 photo software or in common photo editing programs such as Adobe Photoshop and Adobe Lightroom.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] If adjusting colour levels and colour balance is insufficient in obtaining a pure white background, background removal may be required, either with an automated tool or by manual masking by a human editor.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] Professional photo retouching services are often employed for this manual work.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] To display images as an interactive spin on a web page, a JavaScript image viewer is required.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] The JavaScript works by displaying one image after another, giving the feeling of the object rotating.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] The user can drag the image left/right (or up/down) as if moving a real object.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] JavaScript image viewers are either part of a hosted 360 image service or a standalone script.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] Hosted services work by uploading images to the service, from where they are served with the scripts.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] Upon upload, hosted services automatically create the spin, resize and optimise the images for fast loading.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] Image optimisation is of particular importance for 360 spin because the total file size of 36 or more images is considerable.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] Hosted services reduce file size and often deliver the images from a CDN, helping the spin to download quickly.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] Hosted 360 services can also serve spins as GIFs or videos, which are suitable for embedding spins in social media and other websites where JavaScript is not permitted.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] Standalone scripts are installed on a web server, with some basic configuration.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] Images should be resized and optimized either before upload or on the server by an image processing service.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] Some ecommerce sites automatically resize and optimize images on upload, which can accelerate the configuration process.
[src:photography/360-product-photography] If using an ecommerce platform there are plugins to make it faster to configure and embed 360 spin scripts in product pages.
[src:photography/99-cent-ii-diptychon] The work depicts a view of the interior of a 99 Cents Only Store in Los Angeles, with numerous aisles depicting goods.
[src:photography/99-cent-ii-diptychon] It was digitally altered to reduce perspective.
[src:photography/99-cent-ii-diptychon] The photograph is a chromogenic color print or c-print.
[src:photography/99-cent-ii-diptychon] There were 6 sets made and mounted on an acrylic sheet.
[src:photography/99-cent-ii-diptychon] The photographs have a size of 2.07 by 3.37 metres (6.8 ft × 11.1 ft).
[src:photography/99-cent-ii-diptychon] On this work, we can see a supermarket with shelves and many very colorful products, which capture the viewers attention.
[src:photography/99-cent-ii-diptychon] Not only are the products colorful, but they also have all the same price.
[src:photography/99-cent-ii-diptychon] The image was taken in a store of an American retail chain which sells products at 99 cents.
[src:photography/99-cent-ii-diptychon] The photograph is constructed like an architectural drawing with the horizontal shelves of the supermarket perpendicular to its vertical columns.
[src:photography/99-cent-ii-diptychon] Hence the innumerable retouchings, which tip the works over into artifice.
[src:photography/99-cent-ii-diptychon] And to quote Andreas Gursky: “Social criticism is up to you to see.
[src:photography/99-cent-ii-diptychon] The work became famous as being the most expensive photograph in the world when it was auctioned at Sotheby's on February 7, 2007, for a price of US$3.34 million.
[src:photography/99-cent-ii-diptychon] Another auction in New York in May 2006 fetched $2.25 million for a second print, and a third print sold for $2.48 million in November 2006 at a New York gallery.
[src:photography/99-cent-ii-diptychon] These would be the fourth and sixth-most costly photographs sold, as of 2011.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] There has been no commonly used definition of the term "abstract photography".
[src:photography/abstract-photography] The term is both inclusive of a wide range of visual representations and explicit in its categorization of a type of photography that is visibly ambiguous by its very nature.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] Many photographers, critics, art historians and others have written or spoken about abstract photography without attempting to formalize a specific meaning.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] Photographer and Professor of Psychology John Suler, in his essay *Photographic Psychology: Image and Psyche,* said that "An abstract photograph draws away from that which is realistic or literal.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] It draws away from natural appearances and recognizable subjects in the actual world.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] Some people even say it departs from true meaning, existence, and reality itself.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] It stands apart from the concrete whole with its purpose instead depending on conceptual meaning and intrinsic form....Here's the acid test: If you look at a photo and there's a voice inside you that says 'What is it?'….Well, there you go.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] German photographer and photographic theorist Gottfried Jäger used the term "concrete photography", playing off the term "concrete art", to describe a particular kind of abstract photography.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] More recently conceptual artist Mel Bochner hand wrote a quote from the Encyclopædia Britannica that said "Photography cannot record abstract ideas." on a note card, then photographed it and printed it using six different photographic processes.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] He turned the words, the concept and the visualization of the concept into art itself, and in doing so created a work that presented yet another type of abstract photography, again without ever defining the term itself.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] Some of the earliest images of what may be called abstract photography appeared within the first decade after the invention of the craft.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] In 1842 John William Draper created images with a spectroscope, which dispersed light rays into a then previously unrecorded visible pattern.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] The prints he made had no reference to the reality of the visible world that other photographers then recorded, and they demonstrated photography's unprecedented ability to transform what had previously been invisible into a tangible presence.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] Draper saw his images as science records rather than art, but their artistic quality is appreciated today for their groundbreaking status and their intrinsic individuality.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] Another early photographer, Anna Atkins in England, produced a self-published book of photograms made by placing dried algae directly on cyanotype paper.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] Intended as a scientific study, the stark white on blue images have an ethereal abstract quality due to the negative imaging and lack of natural context for the plants.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] The discovery of the X-ray in 1895 and radioactivity in 1896 caused a great public fascination with things that were previously invisible or unseen.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] In response, photographers began to explore how they could capture what could not be seen by normal human vision.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] About this same time Swedish author and artist August Strindberg experimented with subjecting saline solutions on photographic plates to heat and cold.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] The images he produced with these experiments were indefinite renderings of what could not otherwise be seen and were thoroughly abstract in their presentation.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] Near the turn of the century Louis Daguerre in France tried to capture images of mental processes by pressing unexposed plates to the foreheads of sitters and urging them to project images from their minds onto the plates.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] The photographs he produced were blurry and indefinite, yet Daguerre was convinced that what he called "thought vibrations" were indistinguishable from light rays.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] During the first decade of the 20th century there was a wave of artistic exploration that hastened the transition in painting and sculpture from Impressionism and Post-Impressionism to Cubism and Futurism.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] Beginning in 1903 a series of annual art exhibitions in Paris called the Salon d'Automne introduced the public to then radical vision of artists like Cézanne, Picasso, Marcel Duchamp, Francis Picabia, František Kupka, Albert Gleizes, and Jean Metzinger.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] A decade later the Armory Show in New York created a scandal by showing completely abstract works by Kandinsky, Braque, Duchamp, Robert Delaunay and others.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] The public's interest in and sometimes repulsion to abstract art was duly noted by some of the more creative photographers of the period.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] By 1910, in New York Alfred Stieglitz began to show abstract painters like Marsden Hartley and Arthur Dove at his 291 art gallery, which had previously exhibited only pictorial photography.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] Photographers like Stieglitz, Paul Strand and Edward Steichen all experimented with depictive subjects photographed in abstract compositions.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] The first publicly exhibited images that are now recognized as abstract photographs were a series called *Symmetrical Patterns from Natural Forms,* shown by Erwin Quedenfeldt in Cologne in 1914.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] Two years later Alvin Langdon Coburn began experimenting with a series he called *Vortographs*.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] During one six-week period in 1917 he took about two dozen photographs with a camera outfitted with a multi-faceted prism.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] The resulting images were purposely unrelated to the realities he saw and to his previous portraits and cityscapes.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] He wrote "Why should not the camera throw off the shackles of contemporary representations…?
[src:photography/abstract-photography] In the 1920s and 1930s there was a significant increase in the number of photographers who explored abstract imagery.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] In Europe, Prague became a center of avant-garde photography, with František Drtikol, Jaroslav Rössler, Josef Sudek and Jaromír Funke all creating photographs influenced by Cubism and Futurism.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] Rössler's images in particular went beyond representational abstraction to pure abstractions of light and shadow.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] László Moholy-Nagy, a leader of the Bauhaus school of modernism, experimented with the abstract qualities of the photogram.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] Some photographers during this time also pushed the boundaries of conventional imagery by incorporating the visions of surrealism or futurism into their work.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] Man Ray, Maurice Tabard, André Kertész, Curtis Moffat and Filippo Masoero were some of the best known artists who produced startling imagery that questioned both reality and perspective.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] Both during and after World War II photographers such as Minor White, Aaron Siskind, Henry Holmes Smith and Lotte Jacobi explored compositions of found objects in ways that demonstrated even our natural world has elements of abstraction embedded in it.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] Frederick Sommer broke new ground in 1950 by photographing purposely rearranged found objects, resulting in ambiguous images that could be widely interpreted.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] He chose to title one particular enigmatic image *The Sacred Wood*, after T.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] The 1960s were marked uninhibited explorations in to the limits of photographic media at the time, starting with photographers who assembled or re-assembled their own and/or found images, such as Ray K.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] Metzker, Robert Heinecken and Walter Chappell.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] Neumann developed chemograms, which are products of both photographic processing and painting on photographic paper.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] Before the spread of computers and the use of image processing software the process of creating chemograms can be considered an early form of analog post-production, in which the original image is altered after the enlarging process.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] Unlike works of digital post-production each chemogram is a unique piece.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] Beginning in the late 1970s photographers stretched the limits of both scale and surface in what was then traditional photographic media that had to be developed in a darkroom.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] By the 1990s a new wave of photographers were exploring the possibilities of using computers to create new ways of creating photographs.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] Photographers such as Thomas Ruff, Barbara Kasten, Tom Friedman, and Carel Balth were creating works that combined photography, sculpture, printmaking and computer-generated images.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] Once computers and photography software became widely available, the boundaries of abstract photography were expanded beyond the limits of film and chemistry into almost limitless dimensions.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] Any boundaries that remained between pure artists and pure photographers were eliminated by individuals who worked exclusively in photography but produced only computer-generated images.
[src:photography/abstract-photography] Among the most well-known of the early 21st century generation were Gaston Bertin, Penelope Umbrico, Ard Bodewes, Ellen Carey, Nicki Stager, Shirine Gill, Thomas Ruff, Andrew Prokos, Wolfgang Tillmans, Kim Keever, Harvey Lloyd, and Adam Broomberg and Oliver Chanarin.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] An **active-pixel sensor** (**APS**) is an image sensor where each pixel sensor unit cell has a photodetector (typically a pinned photodiode) and one or more active transistors.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] APS sensors are used in digital camera technologies such as cell phone cameras, web cameras, most modern digital pocket cameras, most digital single-lens reflex cameras (DSLRs), mirrorless interchangeable-lens cameras (MILCs), and lensless imaging for, e.g., blood cells.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] In a **metal–oxide–semiconductor** (MOS) active-pixel sensor, MOS field-effect transistors (MOSFETs) are used as amplifiers.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] There are different types of APS, including the early NMOS APS and the now much more common complementary MOS (CMOS) APS, also known as the **CMOS sensor**.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] CMOS sensors emerged as an alternative to charge-coupled device (CCD) image sensors and eventually outsold them by the mid-2000s.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] The term *active pixel sensor* is also used to refer to the individual pixel sensor itself, as opposed to an array of such individuals, the image sensor.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] In this case, the image sensor is sometimes called an *active pixel sensor imager* or *active-pixel image sensor*.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] While researching metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) technology, Willard Boyle and George E.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] Smith discovered that an electric charge could be stored on a small MOS capacitor, which became the fundamental building block of the charge-coupled device (CCD) that they invented in 1969.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] One of the main challenges with CCD technology was its reliance on nearly perfect charge transfer during readout.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] At RCA Laboratories, a research team including Paul K.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] Sadasiv in 1969 proposed a solid-state image sensor with scanning circuits using thin-film transistors (TFTs), with photoconductive film used for the photodetector.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] A low-resolution "mostly digital" N-channel MOSFET (NMOS) imager with intra-pixel amplification, for an optical mouse application, was demonstrated by Richard F.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] Another type of image sensor technology that is related to the APS is the hybrid infrared focal plane array (IRFPA), designed to operate at cryogenic temperatures in the infrared spectrum.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] The devices are two chips that are put together like a sandwich: one chip contains detector elements made in InGaAs or HgCdTe, and the other chip is typically made of silicon and is used to read out the photodetectors.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] The exact date of origin of these devices is classified, but they were in use by the mid-1980s.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] A key element of the modern CMOS sensor is the pinned photodiode (PPD).
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] It was invented by Nobukazu Teranishi, Hiromitsu Shiraki and Yasuo Ishihara at NEC in 1980, and then publicly reported by Teranishi and Ishihara with A.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] Arai in 1982, with the addition of an anti-blooming structure.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] The pinned photodiode is a photodetector structure with low lag, low noise, high quantum efficiency and low dark current.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] The new photodetector structure invented at NEC was given the name "pinned photodiode" (PPD) by B.C.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] In 1987, the PPD began to be incorporated into most CCD sensors, becoming a fixture in consumer electronic video cameras and then digital still cameras.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] Since then, the PPD has been used in nearly all CCD sensors and then CMOS sensors.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] The precursor to the APS was the passive-pixel sensor (PPS), a type of photodiode array (PDA).
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] A passive-pixel sensor consists of passive pixels which are read out without amplification, with each pixel consisting of a photodiode and a MOSFET switch.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] In a photodiode array, pixels contain a p-n junction, integrated capacitor, and MOSFETs as selection transistors.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] This was the basis for the PPS, which had image sensor elements with in-pixel selection transistors, proposed by Peter J.W.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] Passive-pixel sensors were being investigated as a solid-state alternative to vacuum-tube imaging devices.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] The MOS passive-pixel sensor used just a simple switch in the pixel to read out the photodiode integrated charge.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] Pixels were arrayed in a two-dimensional structure, with an access enable wire shared by pixels in the same row, and output wire shared by column.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] At the end of each column was a transistor.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] Passive-pixel sensors suffered from many limitations, such as high noise, slow readout, and lack of scalability.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] Early (1960s–1970s) photodiode arrays with selection transistors within each pixel, along with on-chip multiplexer circuits, were impractically large.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] The noise of photodiode arrays was also a limitation to performance, as the photodiode readout bus capacitance resulted in increased read-noise level.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] Correlated double sampling (CDS) could also not be used with a photodiode array without external memory.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] It was not possible to fabricate active-pixel sensors with a practical pixel size in the 1970s, due to limited microlithography technology at the time.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] Because the MOS process was so variable and MOS transistors had characteristics that changed over time (Vth instability), the CCD's charge-domain operation was more manufacturable and higher performance than MOS passive-pixel sensors.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] The active-pixel sensor consists of active pixels, each containing one or more MOSFET amplifiers which convert the photo-generated charge to a voltage, amplify the signal voltage, and reduce noise.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] The concept of an active-pixel device was proposed by Peter Noble in 1968.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] He created sensor arrays with active MOS readout amplifiers per pixel, in essentially the modern three-transistor configuration: the buried photodiode-structure, selection transistor and MOS amplifier.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] The MOS active-pixel concept was implemented as the charge modulation device (CMD) by Olympus in Japan during the mid-1980s.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] This was enabled by advances in MOSFET semiconductor device fabrication, with MOSFET scaling reaching smaller micron and then sub-micron levels during the 1980s to early 1990s.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] The first MOS APS was fabricated by Tsutomu Nakamura's team at Olympus in 1985.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] The term *active pixel sensor* (APS) was coined by Nakamura while working on the CMD active-pixel sensor at Olympus.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] The CMD imager had a vertical APS structure, which increases fill-factor (or reduces pixel size) by storing the signal charge under an output NMOS transistor.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] Other Japanese semiconductor companies soon followed with their own active pixel sensors during the late 1980s to early 1990s.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] Between 1988 and 1991, Toshiba developed the "double-gate floating surface transistor" sensor, which had a lateral APS structure, with each pixel containing a buried-channel MOS photogate and a PMOS output amplifier.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] Between 1989 and 1992, Canon developed the base-stored image sensor (BASIS), which used a vertical APS structure similar to the Olympus sensor, but with bipolar transistors rather than MOSFETs.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] In the early 1990s, American companies began developing practical MOS active pixel sensors.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] In 1991, Texas Instruments developed the bulk CMD (BCMD) sensor, which was fabricated at the company's Japanese branch and had a vertical APS structure similar to the Olympus CMD sensor, but was more complex and used PMOS rather than NMOS transistors.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] By the late 1980s to early 1990s, the CMOS process was well-established as a well-controlled stable semiconductor manufacturing process and was the baseline process for almost all logic and microprocessors.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] There was a resurgence in the use of passive-pixel sensors for low-end imaging applications, while active-pixel sensors began being used for low-resolution high-function applications such as retina simulation and high-energy particle detectors.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] However, CCDs continued to have much lower temporal noise and fixed-pattern noise and were the dominant technology for consumer applications such as camcorders as well as for broadcast cameras, where they were displacing video camera tubes.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] The CMOS active-pixel sensor, a type of metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) image sensor, was developed by Mitsubishi Electric in 1992 and NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory in 1993.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] It came after active-pixel sensors that were developed using PMOS technology in Japan by Toshiba.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] It had a lateral APS structure similar to the Toshiba sensor, but was fabricated with CMOS rather than PMOS transistors.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] It was the first CMOS sensor with intra-pixel charge transfer.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] In 1999, Hyundai Electronics announced the commercial production of a 800x600 color CMOS image sensor based on 4T pixel with a high performance pinned photodiode with integrated ADCs and fabricated in a baseline 0.5 um DRAM process.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] Photobit's CMOS sensors found their way into webcams manufactured by Logitech and Intel, before Photobit was purchased by Micron Technology in 2001.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] The CMOS sensor with PPD technology was further advanced and refined by R.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] This led to CMOS sensors achieve imaging performance on par with CCD sensors, and later exceeding CCD sensors.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] By 2000, CMOS sensors were used in a variety of applications, including low-cost cameras, PC cameras, fax, multimedia, security, surveillance, and videophones.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] The video industry switched to CMOS cameras with the advent of high-definition video (HD video), as the large number of pixels would require significantly higher power consumption with CCD sensors, which would overheat and drain batteries.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] Sony in 2007 commercialized CMOS sensors with an original column A/D conversion circuit, for fast, low-noise performance, followed in 2009 by the CMOS back-illuminated sensor (BI sensor), with twice the sensitivity of conventional image sensors.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] CMOS sensors went on to have a significant cultural impact, leading to the mass proliferation of digital cameras and camera phones, which bolstered the rise of social media and selfie culture, and impacted social and political movements around the world.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] By 2007, sales of CMOS active-pixel sensors had surpassed CCD sensors, with CMOS sensors accounting for 54% of the global image sensor market at the time.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] By 2012, CMOS sensors increased their share to 74% of the market.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] As of 2017, CMOS sensors account for 89% of global image sensor sales.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] In recent years, the CMOS sensor technology has spread to medium-format photography with Phase One being the first to launch a medium format digital back with a Sony-built CMOS sensor.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] In 2012, Sony introduced the stacked CMOS BI sensor.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] There have been several research activities ongoing in the field of image sensors.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] One of them is the quanta image sensor (QIS), which might be a paradigm shift in the way we collect images in a camera.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] The QIS idea is in its infancy and may never become reality due to the non necessary complexity that is needed to capture an image.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] Boyd Fowler of OmniVision is known for his work in CMOS image sensor development.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] He also patented the first CMOS image sensor for inter-oral dental X-rays with clipped corners for better patient comfort.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] By the late 2010s CMOS sensors had largely if not completely replaced CCD sensors, as CMOS sensors can not only be made in existing semiconductor production lines, reducing costs, but they also consume less power, just to name a few advantages.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] HV-CMOS devices are a specialty case of ordinary CMOS sensors used in high-voltage applications (for detection of high-energy particles) like CERN Large Hadron Collider where a high-breakdown voltage up to ~30-120V is necessary.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] Such devices are not used for high-voltage switching though.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] HV-CMOS are typically implemented by ~10 μm deep n-doped depletion zone (n-well) of a transistor on a p-type wafer substrate.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] APS pixels solve the speed and scalability issues of the passive-pixel sensor.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] They generally consume less power than CCDs, have less image lag, and require less specialized manufacturing facilities.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] Unlike CCDs, APS sensors can combine the image sensor function and image processing functions within the same integrated circuit.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] APS sensors have found markets in many consumer applications, especially camera phones.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] They have also been used in other fields including digital radiography, military ultra high speed image acquisition, security cameras, and optical mice.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] Manufacturers include Aptina Imaging (independent spinout from Micron Technology, who purchased Photobit in 2001), Canon, Samsung, STMicroelectronics, Toshiba, OmniVision Technologies, Sony, and Foveon, among others.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] CMOS-type APS sensors are typically suited to applications in which packaging, power management, and on-chip processing are important.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] CMOS type sensors are widely used, from high-end digital photography down to mobile-phone cameras.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] A primary advantage of a CMOS sensor is that it is typically less expensive to produce than a CCD sensor, as the image capturing and image sensing elements can be combined onto the same IC, with simpler construction required.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] A CMOS sensor also typically has better control of blooming (that is, of bleeding of photo-charge from an over-exposed pixel into other nearby pixels).
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] Unlike CCD sensors, CMOS sensors have the ability to reverse the addressing of the sensor elements.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] CMOS Sensors with a film speed of ISO 4 million exist.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] Since a CMOS sensor typically captures a row at a time within approximately 1/60 or 1/50 of a second (depending on refresh rate) it may result in a rolling shutter effect, where the image is skewed (tilted to the left or right, depending on the direction of camera or subject movement).
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] For example, when tracking a car moving at high speed, the car will not be distorted but the background will appear to be tilted.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] A frame-transfer CCD sensor or "global shutter" CMOS sensor does not have this problem; instead it captures the entire image at once into a frame store.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] A long-standing advantage of CCD sensors has been their capability for capturing images with lower noise.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] With improvements in CMOS technology, this advantage has closed as of 2020, with modern CMOS sensors available capable of outperforming CCD sensors.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] The active circuitry in CMOS pixels takes some area on the surface which is not light-sensitive, reducing the photon-detection efficiency of the device (microlenses and back-illuminated sensors can mitigate this problem).
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] But the frame-transfer CCD also has about half the non-sensitive area for the frame store nodes, so the relative advantages depend on which types of sensors are being compared.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] The standard CMOS APS pixel consists of a photodetector (pinned photodiode), a floating diffusion, and the so-called 4T cell consisting of four CMOS (complementary metal–oxide–semiconductor) transistors, including a transfer gate, reset gate, selection gate and source-follower readout transistor.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] The use of intrapixel charge transfer can offer lower noise by enabling the use of correlated double sampling (CDS).
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] The Noble 3T pixel is still sometimes used since the fabrication requirements are less complex.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] The 3T pixel comprises the same elements as the 4T pixel except the transfer gate and the photodiode.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] The reset transistor, Mrst, acts as a switch to reset the floating diffusion to VRST, which in this case is represented as the gate of the Msf transistor.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] When the reset transistor is turned on, the photodiode is effectively connected to the power supply, VRST, clearing all integrated charge.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] Since the reset transistor is n-type, the pixel operates in soft reset.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] The read-out transistor, Msf, acts as a buffer (specifically, a source follower), an amplifier which allows the pixel voltage to be observed without removing the accumulated charge.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] Its power supply, VDD, is typically tied to the power supply of the reset transistor VRST.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] The select transistor, Msel, allows a single row of the pixel array to be read by the read-out electronics.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] Other innovations of the pixels such as 5T and 6T pixels also exist.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] By adding extra transistors, functions such as global shutter, as opposed to the more common rolling shutter, are possible.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] In order to increase the pixel densities, shared-row, four-ways and eight-ways shared read out, and other architectures can be employed.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] A variant of the 3T active pixel is the Foveon X3 sensor invented by Dick Merrill.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] In this device, three photodiodes are stacked on top of each other using planar fabrication techniques, each photodiode having its own 3T circuit.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] Each successive layer acts as a filter for the layer below it shifting the spectrum of absorbed light in successive layers.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] By deconvolving the response of each layered detector, red, green, and blue signals can be reconstructed.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] A typical two-dimensional array of pixels is organized into rows and columns.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] Pixels in a given row share reset lines, so that a whole row is reset at a time.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] The row select lines of each pixel in a row are tied together as well.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] The outputs of each pixel in any given column are tied together.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] Since only one row is selected at a given time, no competition for the output line occurs.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] Further amplifier circuitry is typically on a column basis.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] The size of the pixel sensor is often given in height and width, but also in the optical format.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] There are two types of active-pixel sensor (APS) structures, the lateral APS and vertical APS.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] For applications such as large-area digital X-ray imaging, thin-film transistors (TFTs) can also be used in APS architecture.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] However, because of the larger size and lower transconductance gain of TFTs compared with CMOS transistors, it is necessary to have fewer on-pixel TFTs to maintain image resolution and quality at an acceptable level.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] A two-transistor APS/PPS architecture has been shown to be promising for APS using amorphous silicon TFTs.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] In the two-transistor APS architecture on the right, TAMP is used as a switched-amplifier integrating functions of both Msf and Msel in the three-transistor APS.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] This results in reduced transistor counts per pixel, as well as increased pixel transconductance gain.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] Here, Cpix is the pixel storage capacitance, and it is also used to capacitively couple the addressing pulse of the "Read" to the gate of TAMP for ON-OFF switching.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] Such pixel readout circuits work best with low capacitance photoconductor detectors such as amorphous selenium.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] Many different pixel designs have been proposed and fabricated.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] The standard pixel uses the fewest wires and the fewest, most tightly packed transistors possible for an active pixel.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] It is important that the active circuitry in a pixel take up as little space as possible to allow more room for the photodetector.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] High transistor count hurts fill factor, that is, the percentage of the pixel area that is sensitive to light.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] Pixel size can be traded for desirable qualities such as noise reduction or reduced image lag.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] Noise is a measure of the accuracy with which the incident light can be measured.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] Lag occurs when traces of a previous frame remain in future frames, i.e. the pixel is not fully reset.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] The voltage noise variance in a soft-reset (gate-voltage regulated) pixel is $V_{n}^{2}=kT/2C$ , but image lag and fixed pattern noise may be problematic.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] Hard reset The pixel via hard reset results in a Johnson–Nyquist noise on the photodiode of $V_{n}^{2}=kT/C$ or $N_{e}={\frac {\sqrt {kTC}}{q}}$ , but prevents image lag, sometimes a desirable tradeoff.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] One way to use hard reset is replace Mrst with a p-type transistor and invert the polarity of the RST signal.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] The presence of the p-type device reduces fill factor, as extra space is required between p- and n-devices; it also removes the possibility of using the reset transistor as an overflow anti-blooming drain, which is a commonly exploited benefit of the n-type reset FET.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] Another way to achieve hard reset, with the n-type FET, is to lower the voltage of VRST relative to the on-voltage of RST.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] This reduction may reduce headroom, or full-well charge capacity, but does not affect fill factor, unless VDD is then routed on a separate wire with its original voltage.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] Techniques such as flushed reset, pseudo-flash reset, and hard-to-soft reset combine soft and hard reset.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] The details of these methods differ, but the basic idea is the same.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] First, a hard reset is done, eliminating image lag.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] Next, a soft reset is done, causing a low noise reset without adding any lag.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] Pseudo-flash reset requires separating VRST from VDD, while the other two techniques add more complicated column circuitry.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] Specifically, pseudo-flash reset and hard-to-soft reset both add transistors between the pixel power supplies and the actual VDD.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] The result is lower headroom, without affecting fill factor.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] A more radical pixel design is the active-reset pixel.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] Active reset can result in much lower noise levels.
[src:photography/active-pixel-sensor] The tradeoff is a complicated reset scheme, as well as either a much larger pixel or extra column-level circuitry.
[src:photography/additive-color] Additive color models are applied in the design and testing of electronic displays that are used to render realistic images containing diverse sets of color using phosphors that emit light of a limited set of primary colors.
[src:photography/additive-color] Examination with a sufficiently powerful magnifying lens will reveal that each pixel in CRT, LCD, and most other types of color video displays is composed of red, green, and blue light-emitting phosphors which appear as a variety of single colors when viewed from a normal distance.
[src:photography/additive-color] Additive color, alone, does not predict the appearance of mixtures of printed color inks, dye layers in color photographs on film, or paint mixtures.
[src:photography/additive-color] Instead, subtractive color is used to model the appearance of pigments or dyes, such as those in paints and inks.
[src:photography/additive-color] The combination of two of the common three additive primary colors in equal proportions produces an additive secondary color—cyan, magenta or yellow.
[src:photography/additive-color] Additive color is also used to predict colors from overlapping projected colored lights often used in theatrical lighting for plays, concerts, circus shows, and night clubs.
[src:photography/additive-color] The full gamut of color available in any additive color system is defined by all the possible combinations of all the possible luminosities of each primary color in that system.
[src:photography/additive-color] In chromaticity space, a gamut is a plane convex polygon with corners at the primaries.
[src:photography/additive-color] Systems of additive color are motivated by the Young–Helmholtz theory of trichromatic color vision, which was articulated around 1850 by Hermann von Helmholtz, based on earlier work by Thomas Young.
[src:photography/additive-color] For his experimental work on the subject, James Clerk Maxwell is sometimes credited as being the father of additive color.
[src:photography/additive-color] He had the photographer Thomas Sutton photograph a tartan ribbon on black-and-white film three times, first with a red, then green, then blue color filter over the lens.
[src:photography/additive-color] The three black-and-white images were developed and then projected onto a screen with three different projectors, each equipped with the corresponding red, green, or blue color filter used to take its image.
[src:photography/additive-color] When brought into alignment, the three images (a black-and-red image, a black-and-green image and a black-and-blue image) formed a full-color image, thus demonstrating the principles of additive color.
[src:photography/photography] Typically, a lens is used to focus the light reflected or emitted from objects into a real image on the light-sensitive surface inside a camera during a timed exposure.
[src:photography/photography] With an electronic image sensor, this produces an electrical charge at each pixel, which is electronically processed and stored in a digital image file for subsequent display or processing.
[src:photography/photography] The result with photographic emulsion is an invisible latent image, which is later chemically "developed" into a visible image, either negative or positive, depending on the purpose of the photographic material and the method of processing.
[src:photography/photography] A negative image on film is traditionally used to photographically create a positive image on a paper base, known as a print, either by using an enlarger or by contact printing.
[src:photography/photography] Before the emergence of digital photography, photographs that utilized film had to be developed to produce negatives or projectable slides, and negatives had to be printed as positive images, usually in enlarged form.
[src:photography/photography] This was typically done by photographic laboratories, but many amateur photographers, students, and photographic artists did their own processing.
[src:photography/photography] The word "photography" was created from the Greek roots φωτός (**phōtós**), genitive of φῶς (**phōs**), "light" and γραφή (**graphé**) "representation by means of lines" or "drawing", together meaning "drawing with light".
[src:photography/photography] Several people may have coined the same new term from these roots independently.
[src:photography/photography] Hércules Florence, a French painter and inventor living in Campinas, Brazil, used the French form of the word, **photographie**, in private notes which a Brazilian historian believes were written in 1834.
[src:photography/photography] This claim is widely reported but is not yet largely recognized internationally.
[src:photography/photography] The first use of the word by Florence became widely known after the research of Boris Kossoy in 1980.
[src:photography/photography] On 25 February 1839, the German newspaper **Vossische Zeitung** published an article titled **Photographie**, discussing several priority claims, especially that of Henry Fox Talbot's, in relation to Daguerre's claim of invention.
[src:photography/photography] The article is the earliest known occurrence of the word in public print.
[src:photography/photography] It was signed "J.M.", believed to have been Berlin astronomer Johann von Maedler.
[src:photography/photography] The astronomer John Herschel is also credited with coining the word, independent of Talbot, in 1839.
[src:photography/photography] The inventors Nicéphore Niépce, Talbot, and Louis Daguerre seem not to have known or used the word "photography", but referred to their processes as "Heliography" (Niépce), "Photogenic Drawing"/"Talbotype"/"Calotype" (Talbot), and "Daguerreotype" (Daguerre).
[src:photography/photography] Photography is the result of combining several technical discoveries relating to seeing an image and capturing the image.
[src:photography/photography] The discovery of the camera obscura ("dark chamber" in Latin) that provides an image of a scene dates back to ancient China.
[src:photography/photography] Greek mathematicians Aristotle and Euclid independently described a camera obscura in the 5th and 4th centuries BCE.
[src:photography/photography] In the 6th century CE, Byzantine mathematician Anthemius of Tralles used a type of camera obscura in his experiments.
[src:photography/photography] The Arab physicist Ibn al-Haytham (Alhazen) (965–1040) also invented a camera obscura as well as the first true pinhole camera.
[src:photography/photography] The invention of the camera has been traced back to the work of Ibn al-Haytham.
[src:photography/photography] He also first understood the relationship between the focal point and the pinhole, and performed early experiments with afterimages, laying the foundations for the invention of photography in the 19th century.
[src:photography/photography] Leonardo da Vinci mentions natural camerae obscurae that are formed by dark caves on the edge of a sunlit valley.
[src:photography/photography] A hole in the cave wall will act as a pinhole camera and project a laterally reversed, upside down image on a piece of paper.
[src:photography/photography] Renaissance painters used the camera obscura which, in fact, gives the optical rendering in color that dominates Western art.
[src:photography/photography] It is a box with a small hole in one side, which allows specific light rays to enter, projecting an inverted image onto a viewing screen or paper.
[src:photography/photography] The birth of photography was then concerned with inventing means to capture and keep the image produced by the camera obscura.
[src:photography/photography] Albertus Magnus (1193–1280) discovered silver nitrate, and Georg Fabricius (1516–1571) discovered silver chloride.
[src:photography/photography] Daniele Barbaro described a diaphragm in 1566.
[src:photography/photography] Wilhelm Homberg described how light darkened some chemicals (photochemical effect) in 1694.
[src:photography/photography] Around 1717, Johann Heinrich Schulze used a light-sensitive slurry to capture images of cut-out letters on a bottle and on that basis many German sources and some international ones credit Schulze as the inventor of photography.
[src:photography/photography] The fiction book *Giphantie*, published in 1760, by French author Tiphaigne de la Roche, described what can be interpreted as photography.
[src:photography/photography] In June 1802, British inventor Thomas Wedgwood made the first known attempt to capture the image in a camera obscura by means of a light-sensitive substance.
[src:photography/photography] He used paper or white leather treated with silver nitrate.
[src:photography/photography] The first permanent photoetching was an image produced in 1822 by the French inventor Nicéphore Niépce, but it was destroyed in a later attempt to make prints from it.
[src:photography/photography] In 1826 he made the *View from the Window at Le Gras*, the earliest surviving photograph from nature (i.e., of the image of a real-world scene, as formed in a camera obscura by a lens).
[src:photography/photography] Because Niépce's camera photographs required an extremely long exposure (at least eight hours and probably several days), he sought to greatly improve his bitumen process or replace it with one that was more practical.
[src:photography/photography] In partnership with Louis Daguerre, he worked out post-exposure processing methods that produced visually superior results and replaced the bitumen with a more light-sensitive resin, but hours of exposure in the camera were still required.
[src:photography/photography] With an eye to eventual commercial exploitation, the partners opted for total secrecy.
[src:photography/photography] Niépce died in 1833 and Daguerre then redirected the experiments toward the light-sensitive silver halides, which Niépce had abandoned many years earlier because of his inability to make the images he captured with them light-fast and permanent.
[src:photography/photography] Daguerre's efforts culminated in what would later be named the daguerreotype process.
[src:photography/photography] The essential elements—a silver-plated surface sensitized by iodine vapor, developed by mercury vapor, and "fixed" with hot saturated salt water—were in place in 1837.
[src:photography/photography] The required exposure time was measured in minutes instead of hours.
[src:photography/photography] The existence of Daguerre's process was publicly announced, without details, on 7 January 1839.
[src:photography/photography] The news created an international sensation.
[src:photography/photography] France soon agreed to pay Daguerre a pension in exchange for the right to present his invention to the world as the gift of France, which occurred when complete working instructions were unveiled on 19 August 1839.
[src:photography/photography] In that same year, American photographer Robert Cornelius is credited with taking the earliest surviving photographic self-portrait.
[src:photography/photography] Moreover, Daguerre informed the Academy of Science in Paris on 7 January 1840 of the invention.
[src:photography/photography] In Brazil, Hercules Florence had started working out a silver-salt-based paper process in 1832, later naming it *photographia*, at least four years before John Herschel coined the English word *photography*.
[src:photography/photography] In 1834, having settled on silver nitrate on paper, a combination which had been the subject of experiments by Thomas Wedgwood around the year 1800, Florence's notebooks indicate that he eventually succeeded in creating light-fast, durable images.
[src:photography/photography] Partly because he never published his invention adequately, partly because he was an obscure inventor living in a remote and undeveloped province, Hércules Florence died, in Brazil, unrecognized internationally as one of the inventors of photography during his lifetime.
[src:photography/photography] Meanwhile, a British inventor, William Fox Talbot, had succeeded in making crude but reasonably light-fast silver images on paper as early as 1834 but had kept his work secret.
[src:photography/photography] After reading about Daguerre's invention in January 1839, Talbot published his hitherto secret method in a paper to the Royal Society and set about improving on it.
[src:photography/photography] Talbot's famous tiny paper negative of the Oriel window in Lacock Abbey, one of a number of camera photographs he made in the summer of 1835, may be the oldest camera negative in existence.
[src:photography/photography] In March 1837, Franz von Kobell, used silver chloride and a cardboard camera to make pictures in negative of the Frauenkirche and other buildings in Munich, then taking another picture of the negative to get a positive, the actual black and white reproduction of a view on the object.
[src:photography/photography] In 1839, Kobell, together with Carl August von Steinheil, reported on their experiments to the Bavarian Academy of Sciences.
[src:photography/photography] The pictures produced were round with a diameter of 4 cm, the method was later named the "Steinheil method".
[src:photography/photography] In France, Hippolyte Bayard invented his own process for producing direct positive paper prints and claimed to have invented photography earlier than Daguerre or Talbot.
[src:photography/photography] British chemist John Herschel made many contributions to the new field.
[src:photography/photography] He invented the cyanotype process, later familiar as the "blueprint".
[src:photography/photography] He was the first to use the terms "photography", "negative" and "positive".
[src:photography/photography] He had discovered in 1819 that sodium thiosulphate was a solvent of silver halides, and in 1839 he informed Talbot (and, indirectly, Daguerre) that it could be used to "fix" silver-halide-based photographs and make them completely light-fast.
[src:photography/photography] He made the first glass negative in late 1839.
[src:photography/photography] In the March 1851 issue of *The Chemist*, Frederick Scott Archer published his wet plate collodion process.
[src:photography/photography] It became the most widely used photographic medium until the gelatin dry plate, introduced in the 1870s, eventually replaced it.
[src:photography/photography] There are three subsets to the collodion process; the Ambrotype (a positive image on glass), the Ferrotype or Tintype (a positive image on metal) and the glass negative, which was used to make positive prints on albumen or salted paper.
[src:photography/photography] Many advances in photographic glass plates and printing were made during the rest of the 19th century.
[src:photography/photography] In 1891, Gabriel Lippmann introduced a process for making natural-color photographs based on the optical phenomenon of the interference of light waves.
[src:photography/photography] His scientifically elegant and important but ultimately impractical invention earned him the Nobel Prize in Physics in 1908.
[src:photography/photography] Glass plates were the medium for most original camera photography from the late 1850s until the general introduction of flexible plastic films during the 1890s.
[src:photography/photography] Because of the superior dimensional stability of glass, the use of plates for some scientific applications, such as astrophotography, continued into the 1990s, and in the niche field of laser holography, it has persisted into the 21st century.
[src:photography/photography] Hurter and Driffield began pioneering work on the light sensitivity of photographic emulsions in 1876.
[src:photography/photography] Their work enabled the first quantitative measure of film speed to be devised.
[src:photography/photography] The first flexible photographic roll film was marketed by George Eastman, founder of Kodak in 1885, but this original "film" was actually a coating on a paper base.
[src:photography/photography] As part of the processing, the image-bearing layer was stripped from the paper and transferred to a hardened gelatin support.
[src:photography/photography] The first transparent plastic roll film followed in 1889.
[src:photography/photography] It was made from highly flammable nitrocellulose known as nitrate film.
[src:photography/photography] Although cellulose acetate or "safety film" had been introduced by Kodak in 1908, at first it found only a few special applications as an alternative to the hazardous nitrate film, which had the advantages of being considerably tougher, slightly more transparent, and cheaper.
[src:photography/photography] The changeover was not completed for X-ray films until 1933, and although safety film was always used for 16 mm and 8 mm home movies, nitrate film remained standard for theatrical 35 mm motion pictures until it was finally discontinued in 1951.
[src:photography/photography] Films remained the dominant form of photography until the early 21st century when advances in digital photography drew consumers to digital formats.
[src:photography/photography] Although modern photography is dominated by digital users, film continues to be used by enthusiasts and professional photographers.
[src:photography/photography] Originally, all photography was monochrome, or *black-and-white*.
[src:photography/photography] Even after color film was readily available, black-and-white photography continued to dominate for decades, due to its lower cost, chemical stability, and its "classic" photographic look.
[src:photography/photography] The tones and contrast between light and dark areas define black-and-white photography.
[src:photography/photography] Monochromatic pictures are not necessarily composed of pure blacks, whites, and intermediate shades of gray but can involve shades of one particular hue depending on the process.
[src:photography/photography] The cyanotype process, for example, produces an image composed of blue tones.
[src:photography/photography] The albumen print process, publicly revealed in 1847, produces brownish tones.
[src:photography/photography] Many photographers continue to produce some monochrome images, sometimes because of the established archival permanence of well-processed silver-halide-based materials.
[src:photography/photography] Some full-color digital images are processed using a variety of techniques to create black-and-white results, and some manufacturers produce digital cameras that exclusively shoot monochrome.
[src:photography/photography] Monochrome printing or electronic display can be used to salvage certain photographs taken in color which are unsatisfactory in their original form; sometimes when presented as black-and-white or single-color-toned images they are found to be more effective.
[src:photography/photography] Although color photography has long predominated, monochrome images are still produced, mostly for artistic reasons.
[src:photography/photography] Almost all digital cameras have an option to shoot in monochrome, and almost all image editing software can combine or selectively discard RGB color channels to produce a monochrome image from one shot in color.
[src:photography/photography] Color photography was explored beginning in the 1840s.
[src:photography/photography] Early experiments in color required extremely long exposures (hours or days for camera images) and could not "fix" the photograph to prevent the color from quickly fading when exposed to white light.
[src:photography/photography] The first permanent color photograph was taken in 1861 using the three-color-separation principle first published by Scottish physicist James Clerk Maxwell in 1855.
[src:photography/photography] The foundation of virtually all practical color processes, Maxwell's idea was to take three separate black-and-white photographs through red, green and blue filters.
[src:photography/photography] This provides the photographer with the three basic channels required to recreate a color image.
[src:photography/photography] Transparent prints of the images could be projected through similar color filters and superimposed on the projection screen, an additive method of color reproduction.
[src:photography/photography] A color print on paper could be produced by superimposing carbon prints of the three images made in their complementary colors, a subtractive method of color reproduction pioneered by Louis Ducos du Hauron in the late 1860s.
[src:photography/photography] Russian photographer Sergei Mikhailovich Prokudin-Gorskii made extensive use of this color separation technique, employing a special camera which successively exposed the three color-filtered images on different parts of an oblong plate.
[src:photography/photography] Because his exposures were not simultaneous, unsteady subjects exhibited color "fringes" or, if rapidly moving through the scene, appeared as brightly colored ghosts in the resulting projected or printed images.
[src:photography/photography] Implementation of color photography was hindered by the limited sensitivity of early photographic materials, which were mostly sensitive to blue, only slightly sensitive to green, and virtually insensitive to red.
[src:photography/photography] The discovery of dye sensitization by photochemist Hermann Vogel in 1873 suddenly made it possible to add sensitivity to green, yellow and even red.
[src:photography/photography] Improved color sensitizers and ongoing improvements in the overall sensitivity of emulsions steadily reduced the once-prohibitive long exposure times required for color, bringing it ever closer to commercial viability.
[src:photography/photography] Autochrome, the first commercially successful color process, was introduced by the Lumière brothers in 1907.
[src:photography/photography] Autochrome plates incorporated a mosaic color filter layer made of dyed grains of potato starch, which allowed the three color components to be recorded as adjacent microscopic image fragments.
[src:photography/photography] After an Autochrome plate was reversal processed to produce a positive transparency, the starch grains served to illuminate each fragment with the correct color and the tiny colored points blended together in the eye, synthesizing the color of the subject by the additive method.
[src:photography/photography] Autochrome plates were one of several varieties of additive color screen plates and films marketed between the 1890s and the 1950s.
[src:photography/photography] Kodachrome, the first modern "integral tripack" (or "monopack") color film, was introduced by Kodak in 1935.
[src:photography/photography] It captured the three color components in a multi-layer emulsion.
[src:photography/photography] One layer was sensitized to record the red-dominated part of the spectrum, another layer recorded only the green part and a third recorded only the blue.
[src:photography/photography] Without special film processing, the result would simply be three superimposed black-and-white images, but complementary cyan, magenta, and yellow dye images were created in those layers by adding color couplers during a complex processing procedure.
[src:photography/photography] Agfa's similarly structured Agfacolor Neu was introduced in 1936.
[src:photography/photography] Unlike Kodachrome, the color couplers in Agfacolor Neu were incorporated into the emulsion layers during manufacture, which greatly simplified the processing.
[src:photography/photography] Currently, available color films still employ a multi-layer emulsion and the same principles, most closely resembling Agfa's product.
[src:photography/photography] Instant color film, used in a special camera which yielded a unique finished color print only a minute or two after the exposure, was introduced by Polaroid in 1963.
[src:photography/photography] Color photography may form images as positive transparencies, which can be used in a slide projector, or as color negatives intended for use in creating positive color enlargements on specially coated paper.
[src:photography/photography] The latter is now the most common form of film (non-digital) color photography owing to the introduction of automated photo printing equipment.
[src:photography/photography] After a transition period centered around 1995–2005, color film was relegated to a niche market by inexpensive multi-megapixel digital cameras.
[src:photography/photography] Film continues to be the preference of some photographers because of its distinctive "look".
[src:photography/photography] In 1981, Sony unveiled the first consumer camera to use a charge-coupled device for imaging, eliminating the need for film: the Sony Mavica.
[src:photography/photography] While the Mavica saved images to disk, the images were displayed on television, and the camera was not fully digital.
[src:photography/photography] The first digital camera to both record and save images in a digital format was the Fujix DS-1P created by Fujifilm in 1988.
[src:photography/photography] In 1991, Kodak unveiled the DCS 100, the first commercially available digital single-lens reflex camera.
[src:photography/photography] Although its high cost precluded uses other than photojournalism and professional photography, commercial digital photography was born.
[src:photography/photography] Digital imaging uses an electronic image sensor to record the image as a set of electronic data rather than as chemical changes on film.
[src:photography/photography] An important difference between digital and chemical photography is that chemical photography resists photo manipulation because it involves film and photographic paper, while digital imaging is a highly manipulative medium.
[src:photography/photography] This difference allows for a degree of image post-processing that is comparatively difficult in film-based photography and permits different communicative potentials and applications.
[src:photography/photography] Digital photography dominates the 21st century.
[src:photography/photography] More than 99% of photographs taken around the world are through digital cameras, increasingly through smartphones.
[src:photography/photography] A large variety of photographic techniques and media are used in the process of capturing images for photography.
[src:photography/photography] These include the camera; dual photography; full-spectrum, ultraviolet and infrared media; light field photography; and other imaging techniques.
[src:photography/photography] The camera is the image-forming device, and a photographic plate, photographic film or a silicon electronic image sensor is the capture medium.
[src:photography/photography] The respective recording medium can be the plate or film itself, or a digital magnetic or electronic memory.
[src:photography/photography] Photographers control the camera and lens to "expose" the light recording material to the required amount of light to form a "latent image" (on plate or film) or RAW file (in digital cameras) which, after appropriate processing, is converted to a usable image.
[src:photography/photography] Digital cameras use an electronic image sensor based on light-sensitive electronics such as charge-coupled device (CCD) or complementary metal–oxide–semiconductor (CMOS) technology.
[src:photography/photography] The resulting digital image is stored electronically, but can be reproduced on paper.
[src:photography/photography] The camera (or 'camera obscura') is a dark room or chamber from which, as far as possible, all light is excluded except the light that forms the image.
[src:photography/photography] It was discovered and used in the 16th century by painters.
[src:photography/photography] The subject being photographed, however, must be illuminated.
[src:photography/photography] Cameras can range from small to very large, a whole room that is kept dark while the object to be photographed is in another room where it is properly illuminated.
[src:photography/photography] This was common for reproduction photography of flat copy when large film negatives were used (see Process camera).
[src:photography/photography] The movie camera is a type of photographic camera that takes a rapid sequence of photographs on recording medium.
[src:photography/photography] In contrast to a still camera, which captures a single snapshot at a time, the movie camera takes a series of images, each called a "frame".
[src:photography/photography] This is accomplished through an intermittent mechanism.
[src:photography/photography] The frames are later played back in a movie projector at a specific speed, called the "frame rate" (number of frames per second).
[src:photography/photography] While viewing, a person's eyes and brain merge the separate pictures to create the illusion of motion.
[src:photography/photography] Photographs, both monochrome and color, can be captured and displayed through two side-by-side images that emulate human stereoscopic vision.
[src:photography/photography] Stereoscopic photography was the first that captured figures in motion.
[src:photography/photography] While known colloquially as "3-D" photography, the more accurate term is stereoscopy.
[src:photography/photography] Such cameras have long been realized by using film and more recently in digital electronic methods (including cell phone cameras).
[src:photography/photography] The history of stereoscopic imaging as an artistic and cultural phenomenon was the subject of *3D: Double Vision* (2018–2019) at the Los Angeles County Museum of Art, described as the first survey of stereoscopic and three-dimensional imaging in a North American art museum.
[src:photography/photography] Dualphotography consists of photographing a scene from both sides of a photographic device at once (e.g. camera for back-to-back dualphotography, or two networked cameras for portal-plane dualphotography).
[src:photography/photography] The dualphoto apparatus can be used to simultaneously capture both the subject and the photographer, or both sides of a geographical place at once, thus adding a supplementary narrative layer to that of a single image.
[src:photography/photography] Ultraviolet and infrared films have been available for many decades and employed in a variety of photographic avenues since the 1960s.
[src:photography/photography] New technological trends in digital photography have opened a new direction in full spectrum photography, where careful filtering choices across the ultraviolet, visible and infrared lead to new artistic visions.
[src:photography/photography] Modified digital cameras can detect some ultraviolet, all of the visible and much of the near infrared spectrum, as most digital imaging sensors are sensitive from about 350 nm to 1000 nm.
[src:photography/photography] An off-the-shelf digital camera contains an infrared hot mirror filter that blocks most of the infrared and a bit of the ultraviolet that would otherwise be detected by the sensor, narrowing the accepted range from about 400 nm to 700 nm.
[src:photography/photography] Replacing a hot mirror or infrared blocking filter with an infrared pass or a wide spectrally transmitting filter allows the camera to detect the wider spectrum light at greater sensitivity.
[src:photography/photography] Without the hot-mirror, the red, green and blue (or cyan, yellow and magenta) colored micro-filters placed over the sensor elements pass varying amounts of ultraviolet (blue window) and infrared (primarily red and somewhat lesser the green and blue micro-filters).
[src:photography/photography] Uses of full spectrum photography are for fine art photography, geology, forensics and law enforcement.
[src:photography/photography] Layering is a photographic composition technique that manipulates the foreground, subject or middle-ground, and background layers in a way that they all work together to tell a story through the image.
[src:photography/photography] Layers may be incorporated by altering the focal length, distorting the perspective by positioning the camera in a certain spot.
[src:photography/photography] People, movement, light and a variety of objects can be used in layering.
[src:photography/photography] Digital methods of image capture and display processing have enabled the new technology of "light field photography" (also known as synthetic aperture photography).
[src:photography/photography] This process allows focusing at various depths of field to be selected *after* the photograph has been captured.
[src:photography/photography] As explained by Michael Faraday in 1846, the "light field" is understood as 5-dimensional, with each point in 3-D space having attributes of two more angles that define the direction of each ray passing through that point.
[src:photography/photography] These additional vector attributes can be captured optically through the use of microlenses at each pixel point within the 2-dimensional image sensor.
[src:photography/photography] Every pixel of the final image is actually a selection from each sub-array located under each microlens, as identified by a post-image capture focus algorithm.
[src:photography/photography] Besides the camera, other methods of forming images with light are available.
[src:photography/photography] For instance, a photocopy or xerography machine forms permanent images but uses the transfer of static electrical charges rather than photographic medium, hence the term electrophotography.
[src:photography/photography] Photograms are images produced by the shadows of objects cast on the photographic paper, without the use of a camera.
[src:photography/photography] Objects can also be placed directly on the glass of an image scanner to produce digital pictures.
[src:photography/photography] Amateur photographers take photos for personal use, as a hobby or out of casual interest, rather than as a business or job.
[src:photography/photography] The quality of amateur work can be comparable to that of many professionals.
[src:photography/photography] Amateurs can fill a gap in subjects or topics that might not otherwise be photographed if they are not commercially useful or salable.
[src:photography/photography] Amateur photography grew during the late 19th century due to the popularization of the hand-held camera.
[src:photography/photography] Twenty-first century social media and near-ubiquitous camera phones have made photographic and video recording pervasive in everyday life.
[src:photography/photography] In the mid-2010s smartphone cameras added numerous automatic assistance features like color management, autofocus face detection and image stabilization that significantly decreased skill and effort needed to take high quality images.
[src:photography/photography] Commercial photography is probably best defined as any photography for which the photographer is paid for images rather than works of art.
[src:photography/photography] In this light, money could be paid for the subject of the photograph or the photograph itself.
[src:photography/photography] During the 20th century, both fine art photography and documentary photography became accepted by the English-speaking art world and the gallery system.
[src:photography/photography] In the United States, a handful of photographers, including Alfred Stieglitz, Edward Steichen, John Szarkowski, F.
[src:photography/photography] Holland Day, and Edward Weston, spent their lives advocating for photography as a fine art.
[src:photography/photography] At first, fine art photographers tried to imitate painting styles.
[src:photography/photography] This movement is called Pictorialism, often using soft focus for a dreamy, 'romantic' look.
[src:photography/photography] In reaction to that, Weston, Ansel Adams, and others formed the Group f/64 to advocate 'straight photography', the photograph as a (sharply focused) thing in itself and not an imitation of something else.
[src:photography/photography] The aesthetics of photography is a matter that continues to be discussed regularly, especially in artistic circles.
[src:photography/photography] Many artists argued that photography was the mechanical reproduction of an image.
[src:photography/photography] If photography is authentically art, then photography in the context of art would need redefinition, such as determining what component of a photograph makes it beautiful to the viewer.
[src:photography/photography] The controversy began with the earliest images "written with light"; Nicéphore Niépce, Louis Daguerre, and others among the very earliest photographers were met with acclaim, but some questioned if their work met the definitions and purposes of art.
[src:photography/photography] Clive Bell in his classic essay *Art* states that only "significant form" can distinguish art from what is not art.
[src:photography/photography] On 7 February 2007, Sotheby's London sold the 2001 photograph *99 Cent II Diptychon* for an unprecedented $3,346,456 to an anonymous bidder, making it the most expensive at the time.
[src:photography/photography] Conceptual photography turns a concept or idea into a photograph.
[src:photography/photography] Even though what is depicted in the photographs are real objects, the subject is strictly abstract.
[src:photography/photography] In parallel to this development, the then largely separate interface between painting and photography was closed in the second half of the 20th century with the chemigram of Pierre Cordier and the chemogram of Josef H.
[src:photography/photography] This Neumann chemogram from the 1970s thus differs from the beginning of the previously created cameraless chemigrams of a Pierre Cordier and the photogram Man Ray or László Moholy-Nagy of the previous decades.
[src:photography/photography] Photojournalism is a particular form of photography (the collecting, editing, and presenting of news material for publication or broadcast) that employs images in order to tell a news story.
[src:photography/photography] It is now usually understood to refer only to still images, but in some cases the term also refers to video used in broadcast journalism.
[src:photography/photography] Photojournalists create pictures that contribute to the news media, and help communities connect with one other.
[src:photography/photography] Photojournalists must be well informed and knowledgeable about events happening right outside their door.
[src:photography/photography] They deliver news in a creative format that is not only informative, but also entertaining, including sports photography.
[src:photography/photography] The camera also proved useful in recording crime scenes and the scenes of accidents, such as the Wootton bridge collapse in 1861.
[src:photography/photography] The methods used in analysing photographs for use in legal cases are collectively known as forensic photography.
[src:photography/photography] Crime scene photos are usually taken from three vantage points: overview, mid-range, and close-up.
[src:photography/photography] In 1845 Francis Ronalds, the Honorary Director of the Kew Observatory, invented the first successful camera to make continuous recordings of meteorological and geomagnetic parameters.
[src:photography/photography] Different machines produced 12- or 24-hour photographic traces of the minute-by-minute variations of atmospheric pressure, temperature, humidity, atmospheric electricity, and the three components of geomagnetic forces.
[src:photography/photography] The cameras were supplied to numerous observatories around the world and some remained in use until well into the 20th century.
[src:photography/photography] Charles Brooke a little later developed similar instruments for the Greenwich Observatory.
[src:photography/photography] Science regularly uses image technology that has derived from the design of the pinhole camera to avoid distortions that can be caused by lenses.
[src:photography/photography] X-ray machines are similar in design to pinhole cameras, with high-grade filters and laser radiation.
[src:photography/photography] Photography has become universal in recording events and data in science and engineering, and at crime scenes or accident scenes.
[src:photography/photography] The method has been much extended by using other wavelengths, such as infrared photography and ultraviolet photography, as well as spectroscopy.
[src:photography/photography] Those methods were first used in the Victorian era and improved much further since that time.
[src:photography/photography] The first photographed atom was discovered in 2012 by physicists at Griffith University, Australia.
[src:photography/photography] They used an electric field to trap an "Ion" of the element, Ytterbium.
[src:photography/photography] The image was recorded on a CCD, an electronic photographic film.
[src:photography/photography] Wildlife photography involves capturing images of various forms of wildlife.
[src:photography/photography] Unlike other forms of photography such as product or food photography, successful wildlife photography requires a photographer to choose the right place and right time when specific wildlife are present and active.
[src:photography/photography] It often requires great patience and considerable skill and command of the right photographic equipment.
[src:photography/photography] There are many ongoing questions about different aspects of photography.
[src:photography/photography] In her *On Photography* (1977), Susan Sontag dismisses the objectivity of photography.
[src:photography/photography] This is a highly debated subject within the photographic community.
[src:photography/photography] Sontag argues, "To photograph is to appropriate the thing photographed.
[src:photography/photography] It means putting one's self into a certain relation to the world that feels like knowledge, and therefore like power." Photographers decide what to take a photo of, what elements to exclude and what angle to frame the photo, and these factors may reflect a particular socio-historical context.
[src:photography/photography] Along these lines, it can be argued that photography is a subjective form of representation.
[src:photography/photography] Modern photography has raised a number of concerns on its effect on society.
[src:photography/photography] In Alfred Hitchcock's *Rear Window* (1954), the camera is presented as promoting voyeurism.
[src:photography/photography] 'Although the camera is an observation station, the act of photographing is more than passive observing'.
[src:photography/photography] Digital imaging has raised ethical concerns because of the ease of manipulating digital photographs in post-processing.
[src:photography/photography] Many photojournalists have declared they will not crop their pictures or are forbidden from combining elements of multiple photos to make "photomontages", passing them as "real" photographs.
[src:photography/photography] Today's technology has made image editing relatively simple for even the novice photographer.
[src:photography/photography] However, recent changes of in-camera processing allow digital fingerprinting of photos to detect tampering for purposes of forensic photography.
[src:photography/photography] Photography is one of the new media forms that changes perception and changes the structure of society.
[src:photography/photography] Further unease has been caused around cameras in regards to desensitization.
[src:photography/photography] Fears that disturbing or explicit images are widely accessible to children and society at large have been raised.
[src:photography/photography] Particularly, photos of war and pornography are causing a stir.
[src:photography/photography] Sontag is concerned that "to photograph is to turn people into objects that can be symbolically possessed".
[src:photography/photography] Desensitization discussion goes hand in hand with debates about censored images.
[src:photography/photography] Sontag writes of her concern that the ability to censor pictures means the photographer has the ability to construct reality.
[src:photography/photography] One of the practices through which photography constitutes society is tourism.
[src:photography/photography] Tourism and photography combine to create a "tourist gaze" in which local inhabitants are positioned and defined by the camera lens.
[src:photography/photography] However, it has also been argued that there exists a "reverse gaze" through which indigenous photographees can position the tourist photographer as a shallow consumer of images.
[src:photography/photography] Photography is both restricted and protected by the law in many jurisdictions.
[src:photography/photography] Protection of photographs is typically achieved by granting copyright or moral rights to the photographer.
[src:photography/photography] In the United States, photography is protected as a First Amendment right, and anyone is free to photograph anything seen in public spaces as long as it is in plain view.
[src:photography/photography] In the UK, the Counter-Terrorism Act (2008) has increased the power of the police to prevent people, even press photographers, from taking pictures in public places.
[src:photography/photography] In South Africa, any person may photograph any other person, without their permission, in public spaces, and the only specific restriction placed on what may not be photographed by the government is related to anything classed as national security.
